occurrenceRemarks: It's a horrible cell phone pictures, but I was at Torrey Pines, on the Guy Flemming Trail's beach overlook and you could easily see a half dozen or more sharks near the surface of the ocean below. (you can barely see them here in the mid-right and upper left edges of the photo.) They seem to be lolling around. right in the surf line. Second-hand word from the rangers report they are feeding on stingrays early in the day, then hanging out in the shallower waters to avoid their monster relatives later in the day. Apparently, these juvenile white sharks have been seen here frequently this year: https://www.nbcsandiego.com/news/local/juvenile-white-sharks-shift-south-to-torrey-pines-solana-beach-not-interested-in-humans-researchers/2983283/

occurrenceRemarks: I called this a White Shark for the following reasons: 1) I got clearer looks through my binoculars than I was able to get with the camera, and what I saw was consistent with the White Shark sightings I've had in the same area from whale-watching vessels. 2) Sub-adult and Juvenile White Sharks have been seen consistently in the vicinity of the cement ship between New Brighton SB and Seacliff SB for at least a month this year, and have appeared there in fairly high numbers at this time of year for the past four years, such that it is sometimes possible to see multiple sharks in a short amount of time. 3) I saw at least three individuals in the span of an hour, all in the same general area (roughly a quarter of a mile of coastline.) From what I've been able to gather, the juvenile and sub-adult white sharks are the most likely species to be seen those kind of numbers in that area right now, esp. from shore. I admit this is all very circumstantial, but based on the accounts of (http://www.mercurynews.com/2017/06/12/sea-hunt-spending-a-day-searching-for-monsters/), and recent experience I've had with, White Sharks on this stretch of coast this time of year, I'd be very surprised to learn these are not the White Sharks that have been reported from this area.

occurrenceRemarks: One of four or five sharks all within a short stretch of New Brighton. This was the largest, likely 7-8 feet, so far as I can tell. Although I recognize that it is not possible to make a definitive ID based on these photos, I believe, based on the number of sharks, their behavior, and my past experience in this location, that these were consistent with the well-known population of juvenile and sub-adult white sharks that have been visiting this area of New Brighton/Seacliff SB for the past few summers.

occurrenceRemarks: I called them White Sharks for the following reasons: 1) I got clearer looks at them through my binoculars than I was able to get with the camera, and what I saw was consistent with the White Shark sightings I've had in the same area from whale-watching vessels. 2) Sub-adult and Juvenile White Sharks have been seen consistently in the vicinity of the cement ship between New Brighton SB and Seacliff SB for at least a month this year, and have appeared there in fairly high numbers at this time of year for the past three years, such that it is sometimes possible to see multiple sharks in a short amount of time. 3) I saw at least three individuals in the span of an hour, all in the same general area (roughly a quarter of a mile of coastline.) From what I've been able to gather, the juvenile and sub-adult white sharks are the most likely species to be seen those kind of numbers in that area right now, esp. from shore. I admit this is all very circumstantial, but based on the accounts of (http://www.mercurynews.com/2017/06/12/sea-hunt-spending-a-day-searching-for-monsters/), and recent experience I've had with, White Sharks on this stretch of coast this time of year, I'd be very surprised to learn these are not the White Sharks that have been reported from this area.

occurrenceRemarks: About 8 feet long. Multiple whitish spots on head. Maybe a Salmon Shark instead of a Great White Shark, but those are the two most likely species to be found here, with this fin profile. We were able to eliminate any other likely species to be found here like Blue Shark, Thresher, Basking, and Mako.

verbatimLocality: California, US
occurrenceRemarks: About 6-8'. Stayed on the surface for at least 10 minutes, swimming slowly, unconcerned by boat. Had white marks on head area (see other photos), could also be scarring.Thinking maybe basking shark from relaxed behavior, but dorsal looks more swept back (salmon or great white-ish). 8/23 Update: Based on raging debate on Blue Ocean's Facebook page, now convinced it is a great white shark. Apparently this female was injured some time ago and has stayed in this general area.

verbatimLocality: Eastern Pacific | USA | California | Orange | off Oceanside
occurrenceRemarks: specimen via Chuck Winkler; female; 1660 mm to notch, 1125 mm girth at origin of dorsal, tissue taken, ask Nefty. Chuck Winkler to email more data. Put in 4th floor freezer, 22 Jun 2009 - RFF. Data via C. Winkler: 48 hour soak, 8.5 in confirmed, bottom set; other species in net but not near shark: 1 halibut, 2 white seabass; measurements and dissection done on 23 Sep 2009; liver, white and red muscle, head and vertebrae taken; photos taken; gut contents taken, fish remains and pinniped flipper and skin taken.  Flipper id'd as juvenile harbor seal, Phoca vitulina, by J. Dines, Mammalogy, LACM, Sept. 2009.  Four gastropods found in gut contents - given to Malacology and id'd as Conus californicus (3) and Crosotta californica (1) by L. Groves, 16 Oct 2009.

verbatimLocality: Eastern Pacific | USA | California | Orange | off Orange County
occurrenceRemarks: specimen via Chuck Winkler, SCMI; water depth given as "30+ fathoms"; water temp at catch location given as "16.7C";  female; 84 lbs. frozen; tissue, stomach contents, intestine contents, gill filaments, vertebrae taken.  Upper lobe of caudal fin broken when moved into tank.  Notes from C. Winkler: "Clear water and abundant bait and good catch the previous 24 hours but conditions changed to green-water and a sparse catch when this shark was caught.  Current was westward.  One spiny dogfish in net just above shark.  No bite marks in it.  Previous water temp was 64 F, then fell to 62 F when shark was caught."
